    <segment id="1" parent="4" relname="volitional-result">I agree with P24 because.... </segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="7" relname="span">

The impression that the phrase &quot;this interface feature is intuitive&quot; leaves is that the interface works the way the user does, that normal human &quot;intuition&quot; suffices to use it, that neither training nor rational thought is necessary, and that it will feel &quot;natural.&quot;</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="3" relname="volitional-result"> 

In common parlance, intuition has the additional flavor of nearly supernatural ability humans possess in varying degrees.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="6" relname="span"> 
Given these connotations, it is as uncomfortable a term in formal HCI studies as it is a common one in non-technical publications and in informal conversation about interfaces. </segment>
